Logistic Regression

Logistic Regression

Whereas Linear Regression can be used to predict a continuous variable, Logistic Regression allows us to make predictions where our dependent variable is a categorical variable.

The Logistic Function is given as

\[ p(X) = \frac{\epsilon^{\beta_0 + \beta_1x_1 + \cdots+\beta_kx_k}}{1 + \epsilon^{\beta_0 + \beta_1x_1 + \cdots+\beta_kx_k}} \\ \text{Odds} = \frac{p(X)}{1-p(X)} = \epsilon^{\beta_0 + \beta_1x_1 + \cdots+\beta_kx_k} \\ \text{log(Odds)} = \text{log} \Bigg(\frac{p(X)}{1-p(X)} \Bigg) = \beta_0 + \beta_1x_1 + \cdots+\beta_kx_k \] where:

  • \(p(X)\) only takes values between \(0\) and \(1\)
  • \(p(X)/(1-p(X))\) is known as the odds and takes a value between \(0\) and \(\infty\)
  • \(\text{log} \Bigg(\frac{p(X)}{1-p(X)} \Bigg)\) is known is log-odds or logit

Create a Training and Test set

Use the sample.split function from the caTools package to randomly split the data into a training set and test set:

library(caTools)
set.seed(88)
split <- sample.split(quality$PoorCare, SplitRatio = 0.75)

The SplitRatio argument indicates what percentage of the dataset you would like to have in the training set. By selecting 0.75, we are essentially calling the function to randomly select patients such that 75% of patients in our training set have ‘good’ care and 75% in our testing set have ‘good’ care.

How would we split the dataset up if we were working with a continuous dependent variable instead?

Use the sample function and the size argument.

df_split <- sample(1:nrow(df), size=0.75 * nrow(df))

df_train <- data[df_split,]
df_test <- data[-df_split,]

Now that you’ve randomly assigned patients to the training and test sets, go ahead and create each dataset:

quality_train <- subset(quality, split == TRUE)
quality_test <- subset(quality, split == FALSE)

# Alternative approach using filter()
qualityTrain <- quality %>% filter(split == TRUE)
qualityTest <- quality %>% filter(split == FALSE)

The AIC value is a measure of the quality of the model. The limitation is that it can only be used to compare models on the same data set. Thresholding

The outcome of a logistic regression model gives a probability, but we would like to convert this to a discrete value, e.g. a binary prediction (‘good’ vs ‘bad’ care). This is done by classifying the probability, \(p(X)\), based on a threshold value, \(t\).

You run into the possibility of Type I (FP) or Type II (FN) error depending on where you set your threshold value. This is often represented by a confusion matrix (aka classification matrix) predicted vs actual classification.

Recall,

  • Sensitivity (aka true positive rate) is calculated as \(TP/(TP + FN)\). In other words, is the proportion of TP to all the actual positives.
  • Specificity (aka true negative rate) is calculated as \(TN/(TN + FP)\). In other words, is the proportion of TN to all the actual negatives.
  • PPV is given by \(TP/(TP + FP)\)
  • NPV is given by \(TN/(TN + FN)\)

A model with a higher threshold value will have a lower sensitivity and a higher specificity (and vice versa).

Example: Threshold value 0.5

table(quality_train$PoorCare, pred_quality_train > 0.5)
   
    FALSE TRUE
  0    70    4
  1    15   10

In this example, we correctly predict 70 cases as being ‘good’ care, but 4 “actual” patients receiving ‘good’ care were incorrectly recorded as receiving ‘poor’ care based on our model at the 0.5 threshold value. Additionally, we have incorrectly labeled 15 pts who are actually receiving ‘poor’ care as receiving ‘good’ care.

In this example,

  • Sensitivity = \(10/(10 + 15)\) or \(0.40\)
  • Specificity = \(70/(70 + 4)\) or \(0.95\)

Example: Threshold value 0.7

table(quality_train$PoorCare, pred_quality_train > 0.7)
   
    FALSE TRUE
  0    73    1
  1    17    8

In this example,

  • Sensitivity = \(8/(8 + 17)\) or \(0.32\)
  • Specificity = \(73/(73 + 1)\) or \(0.99\)

Referring back to our Sensitivity and Specificity curves at different threshold values, this is consistent. Increasing our threshold value, \(t\), from \(0.5\) to \(0.7\) caused sensitivity to decrease and specificity to increase.

As shown in the next example, decreasing our threshold value results in sensitivity to increase and specificity to decrease.

Example: Threshold value 0.2

table(quality_train$PoorCare, pred_quality_train > 0.2)
   
    FALSE TRUE
  0    54   20
  1     9   16

In this example,

  • Sensitivity = \(16/(16 + 9)\) or \(0.64\)
  • Specificity = \(54/(54 + 20)\) or \(0.73\)

ROC Curves

Receiver Operated Characteristic (ROC) curves can help determine which threshold value, \(t\), is best. The ROC curve plots the Sensitivity / True Positive rate (y-axis) against the Specificity / False Positive rate (x-axis) at various threshold values. At point \((0, 0)\) your threshold value, \(t\), is equal to \(1\). Whereas \(t = 1\) at \((1, 1)\) on our ROC curve.

Recall,

  • True Positive rate is another term for Sensitivity
  • False Positive rate (\(= FP/(TN + FP)\)) is the same thing as \(1 - \text{Specificity}\), which is true given that \(\text{Specificity} = TN/(TN + FP)\)
  • High Threshold results in high specificity, but low sensitivity
  • Low Threshold results in low specificty, but high sensitivity

Make an ROC Curve

Use the ROCR or pROC package and the prediction function from our training set, predictTrain to generate an ROC curve:

ROCR package

library(ROCR)
ROCR_pred <- prediction(pred_quality_train, quality_train$PoorCare)
# argument 1 is our model predictions
# argument 2 is the actual/true outcomes from dataset the model is based off of
ROCR_perf <- performance(ROCR_pred, "tpr", "fpr")
plot(ROCR_perf)

  • Add color by setting the argument colorize = TRUE in the plot function
  • Add threshold values to the plot using the following arguments: print.cutoffs.at=seq(0,1,by=0.1) and text.adj=c(-0.2,1.7)
plot(ROCR_perf, 
     colorize=TRUE, 
     print.cutoffs.at=seq(0,1,by=0.1), 
     text.adj=c(-0.2,1.7)
     )
abline(a=0, b= 1) # reference line

pROC package

Unlike with the prediction function of the ROCR package, with roc function of the pROC package, your first argument is the response variable from the training/test set and the second argument is the predicted model.

library(pROC)
pROC_train <- roc(quality_train$PoorCare, pred_quality_train)
plot(pROC_train, col="blue", 
     print.thres = "best", 
     print.auc = TRUE,
     auc.polygon = TRUE,
     )

#print.auc argument prints out the value of AUC
#auc.polygon argument shades in the AUC

Interpreting the Model

Multicollinearity

Recall, this occurs when there is high correlation between independent variables. To test this, check the correlation between the independent variables.

Area Under the Curve

Significance can be determined by looking at the Area Under the Curve (AUC) of our ROC curve, which is a measure of the quality of prediction. A perfect model would give an AUC of \(1.00\) or \(100\)%.

ROCR package

Using the ROCR package and the argument `measure = “auc”, we can calculate the AUC of our model:

AUCperf <- performance(ROCR_pred, measure = "auc")
AUCperf@y.values
[[1]]
[1] 0.7745946

pROC package

Just use the auc function and pass the roc argument in it:

auc(pROC_train)
Area under the curve: 0.7746
# Alternative would be auc(qualityTrain$PoorCare, predictTrain), but we already
# defined pROC_train as roc(qualityTrain$PoorCare, predictTrain), so we can pass that
# and get the same result

Accuracy

Accuracy is another outcome measure to assess the model and is given by the formula:

\[\text{Accuracy} = \frac{TN + TP}{N}\] where \(N\) is the number of total observations

Accuracy can easily be calculated using the ROCR package by using the measure = "acc" argument:

accuracy_perf <- performance(ROCR_pred, measure = "acc")
plot(accuracy_perf)

We can then determine the threshold value that corresponds with the maximum accuracy. As seen in the figure above, our cutoff corresponds with the x.values and accuracy with y.values.

# Get index that maximizes accuracy
ind <- which.max( slot(accuracy_perf, "y.values")[[1]] )
# Calculate accuracy value at the determined index
acc <- slot(accuracy_perf, "y.values")[[1]][ind]
# Calculate the corresponding cutoff at the determined index
cutoff <- slot(accuracy_perf, "x.values")[[1]][ind]
print(c(index = ind, accuracy= acc, cutoff = cutoff))
     index   accuracy  cutoff.44 
10.0000000  0.8282828  0.6705302

Compute the test set predictions:

pred_quality_test <- predict(quality_train_model, type="response", newdata=quality_test)

with ROCR package:

ROCR_pred_test <- prediction(pred_quality_test, quality_test$PoorCare)

Predictions on Test set

Let us now use the model we created based on the training set to make predictions based on the test set. We will then compare our predictions to the actual outcomes to see how well our model holds up.

predict_test <- predict(log_model, type = "response", newdata = test)
head(predict_test)
         1          2          3          4          5          6 
0.04812322 0.09262316 0.21067250 0.11211131 0.16747988 0.03204513

Now, let’s create a Confusion Matrix to see how our predictions compare to the actual outcomes. Let us try this out for a threshold value, \(t\), of 0.5.

table(test$TenYearCHD, predict_test > 0.5)

   
    FALSE TRUE
  0  1069    6
  1   187   11

Model Accuracy

What is the Accuracy of our model?

Recall, accuracy is defined by \(\text{Accuracy} = \frac{TN + TP}{N}\). So in this example, our accuracy is:

\[\text{Accuracy} = \frac{1069 + 11}{1069 + 6 + 187 + 11} = 0.848\]

This can easily by calculated using the pROC package as follows:

coords(pROC_object, 0.5, ret = "accuracy")

[1] 0.8483896

What is the Accuracy of our “baseline” model?

Let’s first determine what our “baseline” model would be by looking at our Confusion Matrix again. Here we see that the most frequent outcome is \(0\), i.e. no CHD event in 10 years. So in this example, our accuracy is:

\[\text{Accuracy} = \frac{1069 + 6}{1069 + 6 + 187 + 11} = 0.844\]

So our “baseline” model gives us an accuracy of \(84.4\)%. The model we developed using our training set with a threshold value, \(t\), of \(0.5\) gave us an accuracy of \(84.8\)%, so our model was just barely an improvement over the “baseline” model.

AUC

Let’s determine the out-of-sample AUC using the pROC package comparing the predicted test set values to the acutal test set values.

# pROC_object <- roc(test$TenYearCHD, predict_test)
auc(pROC_object)
Area under the curve: 0.7421

Thus, we can conclude that our model can differentiate low-risk vs high-risk 10-year CHD patients (AUC = \(0.742\)).

It looks like for the year \(2012\), we are missing 5 observations.

Handling Missing Data

Imputation - fill in missing (NA) values based on non-missing values.

We will use the mice package to perform imputation for the missing values. Knowing that our missing values pertain to the polling data, let’s subset this as we try to perform our imputation.

We can now plug our imputed ‘Rasmussen’ and ‘SurveyUSA’ columns back into our original dataset, polling.

polling$Rasmussen <- imputed_poll$Rasmussen
polling$SurveyUSA <- imputed_poll$SurveyUSA

Create training and test set

  • Training set - data from 2004, 2008 elections
  • Test set - data from 2012 election
train <- subset(polling, Year == 2004 | Year == 2008)
test <- subset(polling, Year == 2012)

What is our “baseline” model?

Our “baseline” model will be the most common outcome. Let’s use the table function on our training set to determine which outcome this is, i.e. Republican or Democrat.

table(train$Republican)


 0  1 
47 53

Here we see that the most common outcome was \(1\), i.e. Republican, with \(53\). So our “baseline” model will be to go with \(1\), i.e. the Republican candidate will win the state. The accuracy of our “baseline” model is expected to be \(53/100 = 53\)%. This “baseline” model is 💩.

A more reasonable “baseline” model would be to use one of the polls, e.g. Rasmussen, and predict that the party favored by the poll in that particular state would win. Let’s create this better “baseline” model now.

# sign() if value is +, gives output +1. If value is -, gives -1. If 0, gives 0.
table( sign(train$Rasmussen) )

-1  0  1 
42  3 55

This better “baseline” model predicts that in \(55\) cases the Republican candidate is predicted to win, in \(42\) the Democratic candidate, and in \(3\) cases it’s unknown.

Compare true vs “baseline” model predicted election outcomes.

table(train$Republican, sign(train$Rasmussen))

   
    -1  0  1
  0 42  2  3
  1  0  1 52

As you can see, our better “baseline” model is a much more accurate - 0.94 - than our previous “baseline” model (\(53\)% accuracy).
